Problem:
Given a non-empty integer array arr[]. Your task is to find and return the top k elements which have the highest frequency in the array.

Note: If two numbers have the same frequency, the larger number should be given the higher priority.

Examples:

Input: arr[] = [3, 1, 4, 4, 5, 2, 6, 1], k = 2
Output: [4, 1]
Explanation: Frequency of 4 is 2 and frequency of 1 is 2, these two have the maximum frequency and 4 is larger than 1.

Approach: HashMap + PriorityQueue
Time complexity: O(n + klog k)
Space complexity: k

Code:
class Solution {
    public ArrayList<Integer> topKFreq(int[] arr, int k) {

        ArrayList<Integer> al = new ArrayList<>(Collections.nCopies(k, 0));
        
        Map<Integer, Integer> freqMap = new HashMap<>();
        
        for(int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
            freqMap.put(arr[i], freqMap.getOrDefault(arr[i], 0) + 1);
        }
        
        Queue<int[]> pq = new PriorityQueue<>((a,b) -> a[0] == b[0] ? a[1] - b[1] : a[0] - b[0]);
        
        for(Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> mp : freqMap.entrySet()) {
            pq.offer(new int[]{mp.getValue(), mp.getKey()});
            
            if(pq.size() > k) {
                pq.poll();
            }
        }
        
        int i = k-1;
        while(!pq.isEmpty()) {
            int[] poll = pq.poll();
            al.set(i, poll[1]);
            i--;
        }
        
        return al;
    
    }
}
